	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName><sic>Sanfrancisco</sic></placeName> <date>March 30th 1864</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">My dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Herewith I<lb/> send you a copy of my Discourses.  I shall<lb/> be happy to have you review it&#44; as I know<lb/> it will be ably and impartially done.  I would<lb/> willingly have sent you some copies for sale&#44; but<lb/> the price is too high.  I published 1500 copies<lb/> which cost me <hi rend="underline">700 dollars in&#45;Gold</hi>.  They are<lb/> sold here for 1 Dollar pr copy.  If you should<lb/> think well of it and could affect a sale in the<lb/> states we might talk of your publishing them<lb/> yourself for the states.  <hi rend="underline">I think I shall sell one</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">thousand Copies here</hi>.  The Book is well received<lb/> here&#44; all the press have noticed it favorably except<lb/> the &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Gleaner</hi>&#8221; which no doubt you have seen<lb/> The &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Hebrew</hi>&#8221; I think will succeed.  The Messenger<lb/> of <placeName>New York</placeName> sympathizes with the &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Gleaner</hi>&#8221;<lb/> in consequence of the appearance of the &#8220;Hebrew&#8221;<lb/> which I consider out of place.  What is your opinion&#63;<lb/>  <persName>Mr Frank</persName> of <placeName>New York</placeName> is here&#44; and on his return<lb/> to <placeName>New York</placeName> wishes to publish my Class Book as the<lb/> whole Edition has been consumed.  He will do so<lb/> in his own responsibility&#44; as the price is too high here.</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>I suppose you have considered that I have<lb/> neglected in not writing to you the fact is that<lb/> very little has <sic>traspired</sic> here worth troubling<lb/> you.  What has <sic>occured</sic> you can learn from<lb/> the &#8220;Hebrew&#8221; and &#8220;Gleaner&#8221; I do not write for the<lb/> Gleaner&#44; but I do for the &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Hebrew</hi>&#8221; from which<lb/> you can copy the several items.  I am anxious<lb/> to see the Hebrew succeed&#44; although I am not<lb/> interested in the same from any pecuniary benefit<lb/> as the &#8220;Gleaner&#8221; would make you believe.<lb/>  The fact is it is jealous and envious and<lb/> wishes to grasp every thing&#8212;and I do not endorse<lb/> such mercenary motives such does not form<lb/> any part of my character.  And therefore I do<lb/> try and assist the &#8220;Hebrew&#8221; such a paper being<lb/> wanted in the <placeName>Pacific Coast</placeName>.  A new society<lb/> is being formed here entitled &#8220;The Universal<lb/> Jewish Alliance&#8221; to cooperate with the Central<lb/> Committee in <placeName>Paris&#44; France</placeName>.  <sic>full</sic> particulars<lb/> you will find published in the &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Hebrew</hi>&#8221; so that<lb/> I need not trouble you with writing it now.<lb/>  I have had but little success disposing<lb/> of your Books&#44; I shall however immediately<lb/> after <add>Hebrew</add> make up my account and forward<lb/> you what I have in hand&#44; and my own <sic>indebtness</sic><lb/> for your publications.  Your Occident I read with<lb/> pleasure&#44; it is the only periodical among our people<lb/> which contains any thing worth reading.</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>I hope I shall soon have the pleasure<lb/> of hearing from you</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In the hope that this will meet<lb/> you in health&#44; happiness &#38; prosperity</p>
			<p rend="indent(8)">Believe me</p>
			<p rend="indent(8)">Yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">H. A. Henry</persName></p>
		</body>
	</text>
